  <chapter number="12" style="c" sid="ACT 12" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="ACT 12:1" />About that time, King Herod seized<char style="sup">[a]</char> a few people who belonged to the church
        in order to mistreat them badly. <verse eid="ACT 12:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="ACT 12:2" />He killed John’s brother James with a sword. <verse eid="ACT 12:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="ACT 12:3" />Seeing how pleasing this was to the Judeans, he proceeded to take it a step further and apprehend Peter
        too (it was around Passover), <verse eid="ACT 12:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="ACT 12:4" />whom he arrested and put in jail, putting him in the custody of four squads (a squad consisting of four
        men) of soldiers who would guard him, intending to haul him up before the folk-people<char style="sup">[b]</char>
        after the Passover. <verse eid="ACT 12:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="ACT 12:5" />So now, Peter was being kept in jail; the church continued praying fervently to God for him.<verse eid="ACT 12:5" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="ACT 12:6" />When Herod was about to lead him forth <char style="it">to his death</char>, Peter was sleeping that
        night between two soldiers, chained up with two chains<char style="sup">[A]</char>. In addition to that,
        two soldiers were guarding the door. <verse eid="ACT 12:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="ACT 12:7" />Out of nowhere, an angel went up to him and a light shined in the cell. He tapped Peter’s chest and woke
        him up saying,</para>
    <para style="p" vid="ACT 12:7">“Get up—quickly now!”</para>
    <para style="p" vid="ACT 12:7">His chains fell from his arms.<verse eid="ACT 12:7"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="ACT 12:8" />The angel told him, “Put your shirt and pants on<char style="sup">[c]</char> and put your sandals on.”
        He did just that.</para>
    <para style="p" vid="ACT 12:8">He <char style="it">then </char>says to him, “Put your jacket<char style="sup">[d]</char> on and follow
        me.”<verse eid="ACT 12:8"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="ACT 12:9" />Once he left <char style="it">the prison, </char>he followed him, but because of the angel he didn’t
        know that what was happening was for real; he kept on thinking that he was having a dream. <verse eid="ACT 12:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="ACT 12:10" />After passing through the night watchmen’s first checkpoint and through the second<char style="sup">[e]</char>,
        they went to the Iron Gate, the gate <char style="it">people use </char>when carrying things into the
        city. <char style="it">That</char> very gate opened automatically itself for them, and after they left
        <char style="it">the city, </char>they went down one narrow street and immediately the angel left him.<verse eid="ACT 12:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="ACT 12:11" />Peter came to his senses and said, “Now I know for certain that the Lord sent one of his angels and delivered
        me from Herod’s clutches and from all that awaited me from the Judean folk-people.” <verse eid="ACT 12:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="ACT 12:12" />Realising <char style="it">where he was</char>, he went to Mary’s house (Mary the mother of John, who
        goes by “Mark<char style="sup">[B]</char>”), where a good number of people were gathered praying.<verse eid="ACT 12:12" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="ACT 12:13" />He knocked on the outer courtyard door and a girl<char style="sup">[f]</char> named Rhoda went to answer
        it. <verse eid="ACT 12:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="ACT 12:14" />Recognizing Peter’s voice, out of joy she didn’t open the door but ran in and announced that Peter’s
        standing at the door. <verse eid="ACT 12:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="ACT 12:15" />They told her, “You’re crazy,” but she kept on insisting that it’s so. They kept on telling her, “It’s
        his messenger<char style="sup">[g]</char>,” <verse eid="ACT 12:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="ACT 12:16" />but Peter stayed there knocking, so they opened <char style="it">the door</char>, saw him, and just lost
        it. <verse eid="ACT 12:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="ACT 12:17" />He motioned with his hand to get them to quiet down and began to explain how the Lord led him out of
        the prison; in addition, he told them, “Go out and tell these things to James and his brothers.” He left
        and went to some other place.<verse eid="ACT 12:17" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="ACT 12:18" />When daylight came, no small amount of commotion took place among the soldiers: what exactly<char style="sup">[h]</char>
        happened to Peter? <verse eid="ACT 12:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="ACT 12:19" />Herod looked for him and upon not finding him interrogated the guards and ordered that they be taken
        away <char style="it">and executed</char> and left Judea for Caesarea and proceeded to spend time there.<verse eid="ACT 12:19" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="ACT 12:20" />Now he was furious with Tyre and Sidon; but in <char style="it">the</char> solidarity <char style="it">of
        a unified front,</char> they approached him and, once they won the king’s chamberlain Blastus over to
        their side, kept begging for peace on account of their country being fed out of the king’s <char style="it">grain</char>
        <char style="it">silos</char>. <verse eid="ACT 12:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="ACT 12:21" />On a prearranged date, Herod, fully clothed in his regal apparel and presiding in his official capacity
        as judge<char style="sup">[i]</char>, proceeded to address them. <verse eid="ACT 12:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="ACT 12:22" />The populace kept shouting out, “<char style="it">We’re hearing </char>a god’s voice and not a human
        voice!” <verse eid="ACT 12:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="ACT 12:23" />Immediately an angel struck him in retaliation for not coming clean and telling the truth<char style="sup">[j]</char><char
        style="it">by letting that remark slide</char>, and he wound up<char style="sup">[B]</char> being eaten
        by worms and breathed his last.<verse eid="ACT 12:23" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="ACT 12:24" />The Word of God kept on growing and multiplying. <verse eid="ACT 12:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="ACT 12:25" />Having fulfilled their mission, Barnabas and Saul returned from Jerusalem and took along with them John
        who goes by Mark<char style="sup">[C]</char>. <verse eid="ACT 12:25" />
    </para>
