  <chapter number="14" style="c" sid="ACT 14" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="ACT 14:1" />In Iconium events occurred along the same lines: they introduced themselves to the members of the synagogue
        and affiliated themselves with it in order to speak <char style="it">before the synagogue </char>so that
        a great many Jews, and not only they but Greek<char style="it">-speaking Jews</char><char style="sup">[A]</char><char
        style="it">,</char> would become believers. <verse eid="ACT 14:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="ACT 14:2" />The Jews who weren’t converted <char style="it">to the faith</char> went on the offensive against them
        and polluted the minds of the Gentiles, pitting them against the comrades<char style="sup">[a]</char>.<verse eid="ACT 14:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="ACT 14:3" />So then they stayed a good deal of time speaking openly about the Lord, testifying about the message
        of his grace, allowing miracles<char style="sup">[b]</char> to take place through their hands. <verse eid="ACT 14:3" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="ACT 14:4" />The majority of the population was divided: on the one hand there were those of the Jews’ camp; on the
        other hand there were those of the apostles’ camp. <verse eid="ACT 14:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="ACT 14:5" />Spontaneously and impulsively, both the Gentiles and the Jews were joined by their rulers and decided
        to attack them and stone them. <verse eid="ACT 14:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="ACT 14:6" />Realizing what was going on, they got out of there and fled to the cities of Lycaonian, Lystra and Derbe
        <char style="it">specifically </char>and to the surrounding area. <verse eid="ACT 14:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="ACT 14:7" />There they continually shared the good news, the good news of the Gospel.<verse eid="ACT 14:7" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="ACT 14:8" /><char style="it">There was</char> a certain helpless man in Lystra—unable to use his legs—who kept on
        sitting <char style="it">on the ground all the time</char>, lame from the time he was born, one who hadn’t
        walked around <char style="it">even once</char>. <verse eid="ACT 14:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="ACT 14:9" />This fellow heard Paul speaking; after <char style="it">Paul</char> stared at him, and while staring
        sees that he has <char style="it">the</char> faith to escape his affliction<char style="sup">[c]</char>,<verse eid="ACT 14:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="ACT 14:10" />he said in a loud voice, “Get up on your feet and stand straight up!”—and he proceeded to do just that:
        he sprung up and walked around, <verse eid="ACT 14:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="ACT 14:11" />and seeing what Paul did the crowd raised their voices in the Lycaonian <char style="it">language </char>saying,
        “The gods came down to us in the form of these men!”— <verse eid="ACT 14:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="ACT 14:12" />and they proceeded to call Barnabas “Zeus” and Paul “Hermes,” since Paul did most of the talking<char
        style="sup">[d]</char>— <verse eid="ACT 14:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="ACT 14:13" />and the priest of Zeus, <char style="it">whose</char> <char style="it">temple </char>is situated <char
        style="it">right</char> before <char style="it">you get to</char> the city, brought bulls and <char style="it">the</char>
        garlands <char style="it">that sacrificial animals are adorned with</char> to the city gates and, joined
        by the crowds, was itching<char style="it"> </char>to perform sacrifices.<verse eid="ACT 14:13" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="ACT 14:14" />When the apostles Barnabas and Paul heard this, they tore their garments<char style="sup">[e]</char>
        <char style="it">to show how upset they were </char>and rushed out into the crowd yelling, <verse eid="ACT 14:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="ACT 14:15" />“Men, why are you doing this? We too are men who experience passion and pain the same way you do, while
        <char style="it">at the same time</char> telling you the good news of turning away from these worthless
        things to a living God, who made the sky, the earth, the sea, and everything along with them, <verse eid="ACT 14:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="ACT 14:16" />who in the bygone generations permitted people everywhere to go their <char style="it">own</char> way
        <char style="it">and do their own thing</char>—<char style="it"> </char><verse eid="ACT 14:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="ACT 14:17" />and yet He didn’t leave them void of evidence<char style="sup">[f]</char> <char style="it">pointing to</char>
        Him <char style="it">being</char> up in heaven doing good things and being kind, giving you that sweet
        rain which makes for productive growing seasons<char style="sup">[g]</char>, the food injecting gladness
        into your hearts until your hearts are filled to the brim<char style="sup">[h]</char>.” <verse eid="ACT 14:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="ACT 14:18" />Saying these things just barely caused the crowd to stop performing sacrifices.<verse eid="ACT 14:18" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="ACT 14:19" />Now Jews from Antioch and Iconium arrived, talked the crowd into stoning Paul, did just that, and dragged
        him and dragged him <char style="it">until they got</char> outside the city, thinking he was dead. <verse eid="ACT 14:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="ACT 14:20" />While his disciples were standing around him in a circle, he got up and went <char style="it">back </char>into
        the city. The next day he left for Derbe accompanied by Barnabas, <verse eid="ACT 14:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="ACT 14:21" />and after he proclaimed the good news <char style="it">of the Gospel </char>to that city and made a decent
        number of disciples there, returned to Lystra, <char style="it">then </char>to Iconium, and <char style="it">then
        </char>to Antioch, <verse eid="ACT 14:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="ACT 14:22" />getting the life-being<char style="sup">[i]</char> of the disciples to rely<char style="sup">[j]</char>
        <char style="it">on the Lord</char>, encouraging them to stick with the faith and advising them <char
        style="it">by saying </char>that a lot of difficulties and intense pressure<char style="sup">[k]</char>
        <char style="it">will occur and </char>must <char style="it">be endured</char><char style="sup">[l]</char>
        in order to succeed in their life of faith (enter God’s kingdom)<char style="sup">[B]</char>.<verse eid="ACT 14:22" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="ACT 14:23" />Now having prayed, combining fasting with the prayer, he went church by church and appointed presiding
        boards<char style="sup">[C]</char>, and the Lord kept on adding <char style="it">more people </char>to
        those who had already come to believe. <verse eid="ACT 14:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="ACT 14:24" />They passed through Pisidia and came to Pamphylia, <verse eid="ACT 14:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="ACT 14:25" />and after speaking the Word <char style="it">of God </char>in Perga, they went down to Attalia. <verse eid="ACT 14:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="ACT 14:26" />From there they sailed to Antioch, from where they started the trip, and were commended for the mission
        they accomplished by the grace of God. <verse eid="ACT 14:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="ACT 14:27" />After getting there and gathering the church together, they proceeded to report what God did, <char style="it">as
        He was </char>with them <char style="it">on the trip, </char>and to report that He opened a door of faith
        for the Gentiles (i.e. He created an opportunity for the Gentiles to join the faith). <verse eid="ACT 14:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="ACT 14:28" />They continued to spend time—and no small amount of it—with the disciples.<verse eid="ACT 14:28" />
    </para>
