  <chapter number="16" style="c" sid="ACT 16" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="ACT 16:1" /><char style="it">Paul </char>arrived in Derbe and then in Lystra and stumbled across a particular disciple
        there named Timothy, the son of a Jewish woman who was a believer <char style="it">in Christ </char>but
        whose father was a Greek-speaking westerner, <verse eid="ACT 16:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="ACT 16:2" />whose <char style="it">good</char> <char style="it">reputation </char>was attested to by the comrades<char
        style="sup">[a]</char> in Lystra and Iconium. <verse eid="ACT 16:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="ACT 16:3" />Paul wanted this fellow to leave with him, and took him to get circumcised (<char style="it">symbolizing
        his conversion to Judaism</char> <char style="it">and the beginning of his obeying the Law of Moses</char>)
        because of the Jews that were in that locale. You see, they all knew that he had a father who was a westerner.<verse eid="ACT 16:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="ACT 16:4" />As they were travelling through the cities, they committed themselves to keeping an eye on the issues
        that had been decided by the apostles and the presiding board<char style="sup">[b]</char> in Jerusalem.<verse eid="ACT 16:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="ACT 16:5" />So then the churches were being strengthened in the faith and were increasing in number day by day.<verse eid="ACT 16:5" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="ACT 16:6" />After passing through Phrygia and the province of Galatia, they were prevented from speaking<char style="sup">[c]</char>
        the Word by the Holy Spirit in <char style="it">the Roman province of</char> Asia, <char style="it">in
        which Phrygia is located and which borders Galatia. </char><verse eid="ACT 16:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="ACT 16:7" />After they went over<char style="sup">[d]</char> to Mysia, they kept on trying<char style="sup">[e]</char>
        to go to Bithynia, but the Spirit of Jesus didn’t allow them to. <verse eid="ACT 16:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="ACT 16:8" />After making an appearance in Mysia, they went over to Troas. <verse eid="ACT 16:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="ACT 16:9" />A vision was seen by Paul over the course of a night: some Macedonian man stood planted in one place
        begging him, “Cut across <char style="it">the Aegean Sea</char> to Macedonia and help us out.” <verse eid="ACT 16:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="ACT 16:10" />Like he saw in the vision, we<char style="sup">[A]</char> immediately sought to depart for Macedonia
        surmising that God had summoned us there<char style="it"> </char>to evangelize them.<verse eid="ACT 16:10" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="ACT 16:11" />They sailed from Troas straight to Samothrace, and the next day to Neapolis, <verse eid="ACT 16:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="ACT 16:12" />and from there to Philippi, which is a leading colony-city in that part of Macedonia. We were keeping
        at it in this city for a number of days, <verse eid="ACT 16:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="ACT 16:13" />and on the Sabbath we went out the city gates and down by the river, figuring it would be a <char style="it">good
        place</char> to pray. We sat down and proceeded to speak to the women who had formed a group there<char
        style="sup">[B]</char>. <verse eid="ACT 16:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="ACT 16:14" />A particular woman named Lydia, a dealer in luxurious cloth<char style="sup">[f]</char>, a Thyatirian
        sympathizer and near-convert to Judaism<char style="sup">[g]</char>, was listening and listening, as
        the Lord opened <char style="it">her </char>heart to heed what was being spoken by Paul. <verse eid="ACT 16:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="ACT 16:15" />As she was baptized (and her household was too), she asked earnestly, “If you’ve come to the conclusion
        that I’m faithful to the Lord, come stay at my house,” and she wouldn’t take “no” for an answer<char
        style="sup">[h]</char>.<verse eid="ACT 16:15" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="ACT 16:16" />Now it so happened as they were going to a prayer meeting, that some teenage servant-girl who had a spirit
        of divination accosted them, one who brought her bosses<char style="sup">[i]</char> a hefty sum of money
        by telling fortunes. <verse eid="ACT 16:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="ACT 16:17" />She followed Paul around and kept on yelling, “These men are servants of the Most High God, ones who
        are proclaiming what you need to do to set things right <char style="it">with God</char><char style="sup">[j]</char>,”
        about them, <verse eid="ACT 16:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="ACT 16:18" />and she kept this up for several days. Paul, exasperated<char style="sup">[C]</char>, turned to the spirit
        and said, “By the authority vested in me by Jesus Christ<char style="sup">[k]</char>, I command you to
        leave her!”—and it left her that moment. <verse eid="ACT 16:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="ACT 16:19" />Seeing that any hope of generating income departed <char style="it">when the spirit departed, </char>her
        bosses seized Paul and Silas and dragged them to the main town square to where the rulers were. <verse eid="ACT 16:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="ACT 16:20" />They brought them to the magistrates and said, “These here men are agitating our city, seeing that they’re
        Jews. <verse eid="ACT 16:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="ACT 16:21" />They proclaim—impose upon us—sets of rules which are impermissible for us to embrace, seeing that we’re
        Romans.” <verse eid="ACT 16:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="ACT 16:22" />The crowd joined in on attacking them. The magistrates flew off the handle<char style="sup">[D]</char>
        and ordered them to be beaten <char style="it">with rods</char>, <verse eid="ACT 16:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="ACT 16:23" />and after wounding them with many blows threw them in jail and ordered the jail keeper to lock them up
        tightly, <verse eid="ACT 16:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="ACT 16:24" />who, once he received such a <char style="it">stern</char> order, shuttled them deep inside the jail
        and put their legs in stocks.<verse eid="ACT 16:24" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="ACT 16:25" />Towards the middle of the night while Paul and Silas were praying, they kept on singing praises to God
        (and the prisoners kept hearing from them). <verse eid="ACT 16:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="ACT 16:26" />A severe earthquake took place suddenly, one of such a magnitude that it shook the foundation of the
        jailhouse, and immediately all the doors were opened, and all of the stocks, chains, and fetters were
        unfastened. <verse eid="ACT 16:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="ACT 16:27" />The jail keeper was awakened, and seeing all the jail’s doors opened, drew his sword and was about to
        kill himself, thinking that all the prisoners had escaped, <verse eid="ACT 16:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="ACT 16:28" />but Paul called out to him in a loud voice, “Don’t hurt yourself; we’re all <char style="it">still </char>here,
        you see.” <verse eid="ACT 16:28" />
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="ACT 16:29" />He called for a torch, ran in, and, trembling, fell before Paul and Silas. <verse eid="ACT 16:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="ACT 16:30" />He brought them out and said, “Sirs, what must I do to be saved <char style="it">from my wretched spiritual
        and moral condition</char>?” <verse eid="ACT 16:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="ACT 16:31" />They said, “Believe in the Lord Jesus, and you and your household will be saved,” <verse eid="ACT 16:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="ACT 16:32" />and he told him the Word of the Lord, him together with his entire household. <verse eid="ACT 16:32" />
      <verse number="33" style="v" sid="ACT 16:33" />At that moment in the middle of the night he took them into his personal care and dressed their wounds.
        With no further delay he was baptized, he and all who were under his authority<char style="sup">[E]</char>,<char
        style="it"> </char><verse eid="ACT 16:33" />
      <verse number="34" style="v" sid="ACT 16:34" />and he brought them upstairs<char style="sup">[F]</char> to his apartment and sat them down at his table
        and put out a spread of food. He rejoiced with his entire household, as they all arrived at the point
        where they had faith in God.<verse eid="ACT 16:34" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="35" style="v" sid="ACT 16:35" />Now days went by and the magistrates sent the constables saying, “Let those men out <char style="it">now</char>.”<verse eid="ACT 16:35" />
      <verse number="36" style="v" sid="ACT 16:36" />The jail keeper informed Paul, “The magistrates have sent <char style="it">word</char> so that you can
        go free. So at this time, leave and go in peace (<char style="it">i.e., go your way free of conflict,
        duress, or affliction</char>).” <verse eid="ACT 16:36" />
      <verse number="37" style="v" sid="ACT 16:37" />Paul said to the jail keeper, “They beat us in public without a decision handed down from a court proceeding—men
        who are Roman citizens—threw us in jail—and now they want to kick us out <char style="it">of</char> <char
        style="it">jail</char> in secret? No—not a chance—have them personally come over and bring us out themselves.”<verse eid="ACT 16:37" />
      <verse number="38" style="v" sid="ACT 16:38" />The constables told the magistrates these remarks; those who heard this became afraid that they’re <char
        style="it">indeed </char>Roman citizens. <verse eid="ACT 16:38" />
      <verse number="39" style="v" sid="ACT 16:39" />They came and pleaded with them, brought them out, and kept on asking them to leave the city. <verse eid="ACT 16:39" />
      <verse number="40" style="v" sid="ACT 16:40" />After leaving the jail, they went to Lidia’s house <char style="it">and were hosted there</char>, and
        once they saw comrades, they comforted them, and they <char style="it">finally </char>departed.<verse eid="ACT 16:40" />
    </para>
