  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="18" style="c" sid="ACT 18" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="ACT 18:1" />After this <char style="it">Paul </char>got himself away from Athens and went to Corinth. <verse eid="ACT 18:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="ACT 18:2" />He found a certain Jew by the name of Aquila, who grew up in Pontus but had recently come from Italy,
        and Priscilla his wife, <char style="it">who had both come</char> because of Claudius’s order to expel
        all the Jews from Rome, and went to them. <verse eid="ACT 18:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="ACT 18:3" />Being of the same trade, he proceeded to take up residence near them and to start working. In this regard
        they were tent makers by trade. <verse eid="ACT 18:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="ACT 18:4" />He kept on reasoning <char style="it">and</char> <char style="it">trying to win over those </char>in
        the synagogue every Sabbath, Sabbath after Sabbath, and was persuading Jews and westerners time and again.<verse eid="ACT 18:4" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="ACT 18:5" />As they (Silas and Timothy) came over from Macedonia, Paul continued to devote himself to <char style="it">the
        preaching of </char>the Word, solemnly declaring to the Jews that Jesus is the Messiah. <verse eid="ACT 18:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="ACT 18:6" />As they were deployed against him hurling abuses, he shook out his clothing <char style="it">signaling
        his having nothing to do with them </char>and<char style="it"> </char>said, “You’re to blame for your
        own destruction<char style="sup">[a]</char>! I’m wiping my hands of it<char style="sup">[b]</char>! From
        now on, I’m going to the Gentiles.” <verse eid="ACT 18:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="ACT 18:7" />He left there and was taken into the home of<char style="sup">[c]</char> someone named Titius Justus,
        a pious God-worshipper, whose house was next-door to the synagogue.<verse eid="ACT 18:7" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="ACT 18:8" />Now the synagogue head Crispus came to have faith in the Lord together with his entire household, and
        hearing <char style="it">this</char>,<char style="it"> </char>many of the Corinthians started to have
        faith <char style="it">in the Lord </char>and were being baptized. <verse eid="ACT 18:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="ACT 18:9" />The Lord spoke to Paul at night in a dream, “Don’t fall into fear<char style="sup">[d]</char>—no—keep
        on talking and don’t fall silent, <verse eid="ACT 18:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="ACT 18:10" />because I am with you and no one can lay a hand on you to harm you, because a <char style="it">dedicated</char>
        group of people<char style="sup">[e]</char> are with me—a great many of them—in this city.” <verse eid="ACT 18:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="ACT 18:11" />So for a year and a half he filled the role of teacher<char style="sup">[f]</char> among them, teaching
        them the Word of God.<verse eid="ACT 18:11" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="ACT 18:12" />While Gallio was the <char style="it">Roman </char>proconsul of Achaia, the Jews, united in heart, mind,
        and purpose, jumped Paul and brought him to the courtroom where <char style="it">Gallio</char> sat as
        judge<char style="sup">[g]</char>, <verse eid="ACT 18:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="ACT 18:13" />saying “This guy uses the Law <char style="it">of Moses</char> to convince people to not be piously devoted
        to God and to not worship Him.” <verse eid="ACT 18:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="ACT 18:14" /><char style="it">Just</char> as Paul was about to open his mouth <char style="it">to speak, </char>Gallio
        said to the Jews, “Oh you Jews! If this really was some wrong-doing or nefarious crime, I would’ve put
        up with this from you while<char style="it"> </char>complying with the methodology <char style="it">of</char>
        <char style="it">a court</char> <char style="it">proceeding</char>. <verse eid="ACT 18:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="ACT 18:15" />But issues concerning concepts, authority, reputations, law, <char style="it">etc.</char> that are specific
        to you are <char style="it">to be </char>monitored by you; I do not wish to be a judge who decides these
        matters,” <verse eid="ACT 18:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="ACT 18:16" />and dismissed their case. <verse eid="ACT 18:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="ACT 18:17" />Everyone<char style="sup">[h]</char> got ahold of the synagogue head Sosthenes and began to beat him
        <char style="it">right there</char> in the courtroom<char style="sup">[g]</char>, and Gallio had no intention
        of doing anything about it.<verse eid="ACT 18:17" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="ACT 18:18" />Paul continued to stay with the comrades<char style="sup">[i]</char> for a good number of days more,
        said goodbye to them, and proceeded to sail to Syria, accompanied by Priscilla and Aquila<char style="sup">[A]</char>,
        after shaving his head in Cenchreae, since, you see, he was holding fast to <char style="it">the restrictions
        that come with an Old Testament pledge called a</char> <char style="it">Nazirite</char> vow. <verse eid="ACT 18:18" />
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="ACT 18:19" />They arrived in Ephesus, and he left those others there, but he for his part went to the synagogue and
        proceeded to reason with the Jews. <verse eid="ACT 18:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="ACT 18:20" />When they asked him to stay for an even longer time, he wouldn’t acquiesce, <verse eid="ACT 18:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="ACT 18:21" />but said goodbye instead, “If it’s God’s will, I’ll come back <char style="it">and visit</char> you again”
        <char style="it">and</char> put out to sea from Ephesus. <verse eid="ACT 18:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="ACT 18:22" />After he went down to Caesarea and went over and greeted the church, he went down to Antioch. <verse eid="ACT 18:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="ACT 18:23" />After spending some time <char style="it">there</char>, he left and went through one part of Galatia
        after another and Phrygia too, putting the disciples on a firm footing.<verse eid="ACT 18:23" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="ACT 18:24" />Now a certain Jew who grew up in Alexandrian named Apollos, a man who was quite the scholar, arrived
        in Ephesus<char style="sup">[B]</char>, being proficient and capable in the Scriptures. <verse eid="ACT 18:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="ACT 18:25" />This fellow was schooled<char style="sup">[j]</char> in the Way of the Lord, and as he was fervent—boiling-over
        really—in the Spirit, he went about speaking and kept meticulously teaching on the subject of Jesus,
        understanding John’s baptism only. <verse eid="ACT 18:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="ACT 18:26" />In addition this fellow began to speak boldly and freely in the synagogue. Once Priscilla and Aquila
        heard him, they took him aside and correctly explained to him the Way of the Lord. <verse eid="ACT 18:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="ACT 18:27" />As he was wanting to tour in Achaia, prompted <char style="it">to do so </char>the comrades wrote a letter
        of recommendation to the disciples <char style="it">there </char>to receive him<char style="it">, </char>who
        when he arrived was joined in tight unison<char style="sup">[k]</char> with those who had become believers
        through the grace <char style="it">of God</char>. <verse eid="ACT 18:27" />
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="ACT 18:28" />The fact is, he kept on overwhelming the Jews in public with refutations, vehemently showing with specifics
        through the Scriptures that Jesus is the Messiah.<verse eid="ACT 18:28" />
    </para>
