  <chapter number="26" style="c" sid="ACT 26" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="ACT 26:1" />Agrippa said to Paul, “Are you allowed to speak for yourself?” Paul then put his hand up<char style="sup">[a]</char>
        and proceeded to issue a rebuttal: <verse eid="ACT 26:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="ACT 26:2" />“In regard to everything I’m accused of by the Jews, King Agrippa, I consider myself fortunate<char style="sup">[b]</char>
        that I’m going to be giving a rebuttal before you today, <verse eid="ACT 26:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="ACT 26:3" />especially with you being an expert in anything that has to do with the Jewish people and in their issues
        and disputes as well. Therefore, I ask <char style="it">you </char>to patiently listen to me.<verse eid="ACT 26:3" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="ACT 26:4" />”So now, all the Judeans have known firsthand the way I lived from the time I was a youth, <char style="it">namely</char>
        what happened from the time it all started <char style="it">when I was </char>among my fellow countrymen
        and <char style="it">was living </char>in Jerusalem, <verse eid="ACT 26:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="ACT 26:5" />knowing me the entire time then. <char style="it">What they would say </char>about it<char style="it">
        </char>if they were put on the stand to testify is that I lived <char style="it">the life of</char> a
        Pharisee, adhering to the strictness of our religion sect. <verse eid="ACT 26:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="ACT 26:6" />At the moment I’m on trial standing <char style="it">before you defending myself</char> for the hope
        of our ancestors’ promises, which God <char style="it">caused to</char> come into being; <verse eid="ACT 26:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="ACT 26:7" />for<char style="it"> a hope </char>which our <char style="it">fellow-countrymen, descendants of the same
        </char>twelve tribes <char style="it">of Israel,</char> are hoping to attain, earnestly performing rituals
        of worship day and night; for a hope for which I’m defending myself from charges which the Jews are pressing,
        Your Highness<char style="sup">[c]</char>.<verse eid="ACT 26:7" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="ACT 26:8" />”Why have you all decided that it’s too far-fetched to believe that there’s life after death, <char style="it">God
        causing a person to live in a state of bliss</char><char style="sup">[d]</char>? <verse eid="ACT 26:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="ACT 26:9" />Now—yes—I deemed it necessary to get personally involved in and actively participate in opposing everything
        Jesus of Nazareth stands for<char style="sup">[e]</char>, and I did this a lot. <verse eid="ACT 26:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="ACT 26:10" />I did this in Jerusalem and had many of God’s very people<char style="sup">[f]</char> locked up in prison,
        once I obtained the authority to do so from the chief priests, and I cast my vote for them to receive
        the death penalty. <verse eid="ACT 26:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="ACT 26:11" />Going through all the synagogues one after another punishing them on many occasions, I kept trying to
        force them to renounce their faith, and, fuming with rage against them, I continuing persecuting them
        <char style="it">even spilling over into</char> neighboring cities.<verse eid="ACT 26:11" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="ACT 26:12" />”Engaged in such affairs<char style="sup">[g]</char>, walking to Damascus with the authorization and
        permission of the chief priests with me, <verse eid="ACT 26:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="ACT 26:13" />while on the road at noon, I saw, Your Highness, a light coming from the sky overhead—a light brighter
        than the sun—shine around me and around my fellow travellers. <verse eid="ACT 26:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="ACT 26:14" />All of us fell flat on the ground, and I heard a voice say to me in Aramaic<char style="sup">[h]</char>,
        <char style="wj">“Saul, Saul, why do you persecute me? It’s hard to swim against the tide</char><char
        style="sup">[A]</char><char style="wj">.”</char> <verse eid="ACT 26:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="ACT 26:15" />I said, “Who are you, sir?” The Lord said, <char style="wj">“This is Jesus, the one you’re persecuting.
        </char><verse eid="ACT 26:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="ACT 26:16" /><char style="wj">Enough—get up and stand on your feet. I became visible to you for this </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">purpose</char></char><char style="wj">: to appoint you to be an assistant
        and to appoint you to tell others of the truthfulness of</char><char style="sup">[i]</char><char style="wj">
        both </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">the fact</char></char><char style="wj"> that you saw me
        </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">and what I told you then</char></char><char style="wj"> and
        that I will be seen</char><char style="sup">[j]</char><char style="wj"> by you </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">and you will be told more things</char></char><char style="wj">. </char><verse eid="ACT 26:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="ACT 26:17" /><char style="wj">I’m rescuing you and letting you escape from the </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">Israeli
        </char></char><char style="wj">folk-people</char><char style="sup">[k]</char><char style="wj"> and from
        the Gentiles and sending you </char><char style="it"><char style="wj">as a missionary </char></char><char
        style="wj">to the Gentiles </char><verse eid="ACT 26:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="ACT 26:18" /><char style="wj">to open their eyes for the one-time turning from darkness to light and from </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">being </char></char><char style="wj">of the authority of Satan to </char><char
        style="it"><char style="wj">being</char></char><char style="wj"> close to</char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj"> </char></char><char style="wj">God</char><char style="sup">[B]</char><char style="wj">, and
        for them by faith in me to receive forgiveness of sins and their very own piece of the pie, so to speak</char><char
        style="sup">[l]</char><char style="wj">, among the people whom God separated </char><char style="it"><char
        style="wj">to Himself</char></char><char style="sup">[C]</char><char style="wj">by means of faith.”</char><verse eid="ACT 26:18" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="ACT 26:19" />”As a result, King Agrippa, I was not left in a state of disobedience or disbelief by the heavenly vision.<verse eid="ACT 26:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="ACT 26:20" />On the contrary—I proceeded to tell everyone <char style="it">that they must </char>be changing <char
        style="it">their</char> hearts and <char style="it">their</char> ways<char style="sup">[m]</char> and
        be turning to<char style="it"> where they are</char> close to God<char style="sup">[B]</char> and to
        perform deeds reflective of<char style="sup">[n]</char> a change of heart and of ways, first <char style="it">telling
        this </char>to those in Damascus but not only to them but to those in Jerusalem, to the entire Judean
        countryside, and to the Gentiles. <verse eid="ACT 26:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="ACT 26:21" />Because of all of this, the Judeans seized me when I was in the temple and proceeded to try to have me
        killed. <verse eid="ACT 26:21" />
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="ACT 26:22" />So getting the help of <char style="it">that which comes </char>from God up until this moment, I have
        taken a stand<char style="sup">[o]</char> and am testifying in court today, letting the insignificant
        and the great as well know the truthfulness of what was going to happen, telling them nothing apart from
        what the prophets (and Moses too) spoke, <char style="it">which I assert is this</char>: <verse eid="ACT 26:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="ACT 26:23" />#1<char style="it">—</char>The Messiah is capable of experiencing suffering; <char style="it">#2</char>—A
        prototype of those who come back from the dead<char style="sup">[p]</char> is going to announce to the
        <char style="it">Israeli</char> folk-people and to the Gentiles<char style="it"> that there is </char>a
        light.”<verse eid="ACT 26:23" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="ACT 26:24" />While he was <char style="it">still</char> making his rebuttal, Festus said loudly, “You’re crazy, Paul!
        All of that studying you’ve done reading all those books has driven you insane!”<verse eid="ACT 26:24" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="ACT 26:25" />Paul said, “I’m not crazy, Your Excellency Festus, rather I’m uttering sentences consisting of the honest
        truth and of sanity. <verse eid="ACT 26:25" />
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="ACT 26:26" />You see, the king, whom I’m speaking freely and in a straightforward way to, understands these <char
        style="it">topics</char>. In fact I don’t believe that any of these <char style="it">topics</char> are
        over his head; the fact is, this <char style="it">new religion called ‘Christianity’ </char>hasn’t been
        practiced in a way that it’s been kept in the closet.<char style="sup">[q]</char> <verse eid="ACT 26:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="ACT 26:27" />Do you believe, King Agrippa, in the Bible<char style="sup">[r]</char>? From what I’ve seen, I know that
        you believe.”<verse eid="ACT 26:27" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="28" style="v" sid="ACT 26:28" />Agrippa <char style="it">said </char>to Paul, “In a little <char style="it">way</char><char style="sup">[D]</char>
        you’re talking me into making <char style="it">myself </char>a Christian.”<verse eid="ACT 26:28" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="29" style="v" sid="ACT 26:29" />Paul <char style="it">said,</char> “Would to God <char style="it">I would persuade </char>in both a little
        <char style="it">way </char>and in a big <char style="it">way, </char>and not just you only but everyone
        who’s listening to me today, to become like me except for the shackles,” <verse eid="ACT 26:29" />
      <verse number="30" style="v" sid="ACT 26:30" />and the king, the governor &amp; Bernice, and those seated with them got up, <verse eid="ACT 26:30" />
      <verse number="31" style="v" sid="ACT 26:31" />withdrew somewhere private, and proceeded to talk to one another saying that this man has committed nothing
        worthy of the death penalty or imprisonment. <verse eid="ACT 26:31" />
      <verse number="32" style="v" sid="ACT 26:32" />Agrippa said to Festus, “That fellow would’ve walked free had he not appealed <char style="it">his case
        </char>to Caesar.”<verse eid="ACT 26:32" />
    </para>
